I think the problem is the amount of time that is into EQs programming.<br>
<br>
Most of the other games I have seen are designed to have PvP as their core high end game.  With EQ its Raiding.<br>
<br>
What this means is that the vast bulk of R&amp;D spent on EQ is in PvE.  DAoC came closest to this balance, but the PvE world there was small especially at higher levels.  Too small in fact (gee where am I going today...let me see there is Lyonesse and ummm Lyonesse).  There are some great things about the game (corpse runs, a better LFG tool that people actually use, RvR).  But the PvE, never lives up to EQ versatility.  I know its silly but the look and feel of Velious versus Luclin versus Kunark, gives one &quot;something different&quot;.<br>
<br>
The other problem with DAoC is class balance.  My main there was a Theurgist, which when I left was:<br>
- By far the best soloing class in the game, even at the highest levels could solo the equivalent of yellows.<br>
- The most desired grouping class, which I could run an equivalent of a bard song, go afk and the group loved me.<br>
<br>
So, why not challenge EQ head to head?  People try to come up with new ideas.  They all boil down to PvP.  Investors realize to create a world of the PvE complexity of EQ is a huge investment.  Even Sony realizes it and is making EQ2 smaller to start with.<br>
<br>
Cames Houdini<br>
